AGE_COM: U-Pb dating of gabbro in central Washington yielded Late Jurassic age (Southwick, 1974).  Gabbronorite on Mt. Sefrit in Whatcom County yielded Rb-Sr age of 23 Ma; quartz diorite in Snokimish County yielded K-Ar age of 37 Ma and zircon fission-track age of 30 Ma; gabbro of Ingalls Tectonic Complex yielded zircon U-Pb age of 155 Ma (Dragovich and others, 2002).

In northern Stevens and Ferry Counties, limestone has yielded Early Triassic ammonites, braciopods, pelecypods, cephalopods, and gastropods, as well as Early to Late Permian fusulinids, crinoids, bryozoans, brachiopods, and corals (Stoffel and others, 1991).  The Orcas Chert contains Triassic to Early Jurassic radiolaria and conodonts (Brandon and others, 1988).
Metaline Formation contains Early Cambrian to Middle Ordovician trilobites, brachiopods, conodonts, and fish (Stoffel and others, 1991).
Age based on stratigraphic location.

Addy and Gypsy contain Early Cambrian trilobites, brachiopods, and molluscs; suggested that Precambrian-Cambrian boundary in lower part of formation (fossils restricted to upper part) (Stoffel and others, 1991).

Portion of Hozomeen Group included in this unit yielded radiolarians of middle to late Triassic and early Jurassic (Tabor and others, 1994).  Sedimentary rocks of Chilliwack Group (see also WAPMPms) contain Devonian to Permian fusulinids and macrofossils and Mississippian Crinoids as well as detrital zircon U-Pb Late Devonian ages (Tabor and others, 1994, Dragovich and others, 2002).  Sedimentary rocks of the Cultus Formation contain radiolarians of Triassic to Late Jurassic in age (Dragovich and others, 2002).

Sedimentary rocks of Chilliwack Group (see also WAPMPm) contain Devonian to Permian fusulinids and macrofossils and Mississippian Crinoids as well as detrital zircon U-Pb Late Devonian ages (Tabor and others, 1994, Dragovich and others, 2002).  The Nooksack Group contains macrofossils of Late Jurassic to Early Cretaceous age (Tabor and others, 1994).  Sedimentary rocks of the Cultus Formation contain radiolarians of Triassic to Late Jurassic in age (Dragovich and others, 2002).

Reidel and others, 1992, map outcrops in Asotin County as Triassic and Jurassic.  Misch, 1977, reports that the Hozomeen Group is Late Paleozoic, possibly into the Triassic; Tabor and others, 1994, report Permian radiolarians within the Hozomeen group.  Sedimentary rocks of Chilliwack Group (see WAPMPm and WAPMPms) contain Devonian to Permian fusulinids and macrofossils and Mississippian Crinoids as well as detrital zircon U-Pb Late Devonian ages (Tabor and others, 1994, Dragovich and others, 2002).  Coon Hollow Formation contains Callovian to Oxfordian (mid-Jurassic) ammonites;  Wild Sheep Creek Formation contains Ladinian to Carnian (Mid to Late Triassic) ammonites and pelecypods; Doyle Creek Formation overlies Wild Sheep Creek and underlies Martin Bridge Formation (see WATR) of Norian age (Schuster and others, 1997).
Based on fusulinids in limestones and correlation to the Chilliwack Group (see WAPMPm, WAPMPms, and WAPMPmv) (Brandon and others, 1988).

K-Ar and fission track ages from ash partings in coal beds of Puget Group: 41.2 Ma to 45.0 Ma (Turner and others, 1983).  K-Ar age and fission track age on andesite breccia of Tukwila Formation of 45.9 Ma and 41 Ma respectively (Frizzell, 1979).  Foraminifers of Olequa Creek and Aldwell Formation referable to Narizian stage (Walsh, 1987, Snavely and others, 1993).
Foraminerfers referable to Narizian stage (Walsh, 1987).
K-Ar dates of 44-40 Ma for Naches Formation (Tabor and others, 1993).
Warren, 1941, suggests an Oligocene age for the lower Keechelus based on stratigraphy.
K-Ar date from hornblende in dacite breccia is 38.1 +/- 3.3 Ma and apatite fission-track date from andesite flow is 47 +/- 3 Ma (Tabor and others, 1993).

Walsh and others, 1987, report that the Northcraft Formation yielded whole-rock  K-Ar ages of 38 to 39 Ma.  Walsh and others, 1987, and Snavely and others, 1958, correlate this unit and the Northcraft Formation with the Goble volcanic series (see WAEv1b) which is late Eocene to early Oligocene in age (35 to 38 Ma).
K-Ar dating (whole rock) yields ages of 38 and 39 Ma (Walsh and others, 1987).

Luedke, 1998, indicates that some of this unit is Oligocene in age.  Basaltic-andesite and basalt flows along Columbia River yielded K-Ar ages of 27.9+/-1.9 and 28.1+/-2.7 Ma (Phillips, 1987).  The Goble volcanic member is 35 to 38 Ma, based on stratigraphy and isotope dating of adjacent units (Walsh and others, 1987).

The Naches Formation, in general, is considered to be early Oligocene(?) to middle Eocene; the rhyolite and basalt as late and middle Eocene (Tabor and others, 2000).  The Naches Formation also yielded zircon fission-track ages of 40 to 45 Ma (Dragovich and others, 2002, Walsh and others, 1987).

Absolute ages above for Cresent Formation (Babcock and others, 1994).Coccoliths from limy interbeds in Cresent Basalts of Olympic Peninsula assigned to Discoaster lodonensis Zone of early Eocene age (Snavely and Wells, 1984).Foraminifera from siltstone and tuff indicate Ulatisian stage; accreted to continent by Middle Eocene (48 Ma) (Walsh and others, 1987).
U-Pb zircon ages of basaltic andesite (342 -426 Ma) and fossils in limestone of Chilliwack Group indicates Late Devonian to Permian age (Lapen 2000, Dragovich and others, 2002)

Obstruction Formation yielded a fission-track age of 95 Ma, probably representing maximum age of deposition; James Island Formation (of the Lummi Group) contained index fossils of late Tithonian (Late Jurassic) age and Jura-Cretaceous belemnites and radiolaria (Garver, 1988).  Barksdale, 1975, reports that the Buck Mountain Formation yielded fossils of Hauterivian to Barremian (Early Cretaceous); speculates that the Twisp Formation is of middle Jurassic.

The Nooksack formation contains Late Jurassic to Early Cretaceous belemnites (Tabor and others, 1994, Dragovich and others, 2002).  The Lummi Formation contains late Jurassic buchia and possibly ranges into the Early Cretaceous (Brandon and others, 1988).  The eastern, western, and Trafton melange belts of the west-central Cascade Range is considered to be mid-Cretaceous to Paleocene in age; radiolarian within the chert of the Trafton melange range from Triassic to Jurassic (Tabor and others, 1988).

Eagle Cliff basalt yielded Albian-Cenomanian forams (Garver, 1988).  Chert in Lummi Formation contains Early to Late Jurassic radiolarians; Fidalgo Complex yielded U-Pb zircon ages of 160 to 170 Ma and K-Ar age of 155 Ma; Lopez structural complex contains Jurassic to Cretaceous radiolarians (Dragovich and others, 2002).Dragovich and others, 2002, consider the volcanic rocks in King County to be Eocene in age.
Above dates based on zircon U-Pb ages on tuff of Wells Creek volcanics; have been interpreted to indicated crystallization at about 175 to 180 Ma (Dragovich and others, 2002).
The Nanaimo Group contains late Campanian and late Santonian fossils (Dragovich and others, 2002).
Age is for entire Midnight Peak Formation (see WATKv).
Jack Mountain Formation derived from Lower Cretaceous (and possibly Upper Jurassic?) strata (Misch, 1977).
Minimum age not as well confined--estimated to be Cenomanian or possibly as young as Turonian (88.5 Ma) (Barksdale, 1975).

Rhyolite tuff from the Barlow Pass volcanics yielded zircon fission-track ages of 35 to 46 Ma; the Naches Formation yielded K-Ar and fission-track  ages of 40 to 44 Ma; the Silver Pass Volcanics yielded zircon fission-track ages of 50 to 52 Ma (Dragovich and others, 2002).
Rau, 1967, reports foraminifera of Saucesian and Relizian age in the Astoria Formation.

The Montesano Formation contains foraminiferal faunas of the Mohnian and Delmontian stages; the Astoria Formation contains foraminiferal faunas of Saucesian, Relizian, and Luisian(?) stages (Logan, 1987a).

Basaltic gravels of the Thorp Gravel has been dated at 3.64 to 3.7 Ma; volcaniclastics of the Ellensburg Formation has been dated at 4.72 to 10.53 Ma; Hemphallian to Clarendonian fossils (5 to 12 Ma) have also been found in the Ellensburg (Smith and others, 1989).

Zircon fission-track dating from rhyolite in central Washington yielded ages of 22.0 Ma and 55.1 Ma, although the latter was taken from a tuff bed which could have been contaminated by older detritus (Tabor and others, 1982).  The Saddle Mountain Basalt yielded K-Ar and Ar-Ar ages ranging from 6 Ma to 14.5 Ma (Schuster and others, 1997).

Saddle Mountain Basalt yielded K-Ar ages of 6 Ma to 14.5 Ma; Wanapum Basalt yielded K-Ar ages of 14.5 Ma to 15.3 Ma; Grande Ronde Basalt yielded K-Ar and Ar-Ar ages of 15.6 to 16.9 Ma; Imnaha Basalt yielded K-Ar age of 17.3 Ma (Schuster and others, 1997).  The Hannegan volcanics yielded K-Ar ages of 3.3 and 3.6 Ma and fission-track age of 4.4 Ma; Skagit volcanic intruded by 22 to 25 Ma phase of Chilliwack batholith (Dragovich and others, 2002).

Sheppard granite is considered to be of Eocene age (Joseph, 1990).  The Sheppard granite intrudes Upper Cretaceous Sophie Mountain Formation and is cut by lamprophyre dikes dated at 53 Ma; possibly correlative with Coryell intrusive rocks dated at 51-52 Ma (Stoffel and others, 1991).

The Similkameen composite pluton is considered to be Jurassic or Cretaceous in age (Rinehart and Fox, 1972).  The age of the Buckhorn Mountain is uncertain but estimated to be Jurassic or Cretaceous based on radiometric ages found in compositionally similar plutons in southern British Columbia (Stoffel, 1990).

Some plutons may actually be Tertiary in age (example: Railroad Pluton in Chelan County from Cater and Wright, 1967).  Mount Stuart granodiorite western pluton is 85 Ma and eastern pluton is 93 +/- 3 Ma (Tabor and others, 1993).  Spirit pluton (Stevens County) gives K-Ar dates betweeen 91+/-3.0 and 100+/-2.8 Ma; Kaniksu batholith gives K-Ar dates of 92.9+/-3.0 and 99.1+/-3.2 Ma (Yates and Engels, 1968).  The Cooper Mountain batholith yielded a K-Ar biotite age of 48 Ma; most of this unit, however, is mapped as Cretaceous and some Tertiary-Cretaceous, ranging from about 40 Ma to 190 Ma (Stoffel and others, 1991).

More recent references indicate that most if not all of this unit, as well as the other units in the northern Olympic Peninsula are Tertiary, primarily Miocene to Eocene, in age (eg. Dragovich and others, 2002, Tabor and Cady, 1978).

Contains fauna of Narizian Stage (Dragovich and others, 2002).  More recent references indicate that most if not all of this unit, as well as the other units in the northern Olympic Peninsula are Tertiary, primarily Oligocene to Eocene, in age (eg. Dragovich and others, 2002, Tabor and Cady, 1978).

Rossland group is overlain by volcanics of 165 Ma (radiometric age) and overlies metaconglomerate of 196 Ma; in southern British Columbia, contains Early Jurassic marine microfossils (Stossel and others, 1991. Stoffel, 1990).
Ordovician graptolites and brachipods found in Ledbetter Slate (Park and Cannon, 1943, Joseph, 1990a).

Oligocene flora found in tuff beds of Tom Thumb (Muessig, 1967).  Eagle Creek Formation is considered to be early Miocene (Korosec, 1987, Phillips, 1987).  Toutle Formation is of late Eocene to early Oligocene age (Roberts, 1958).
Rau, 1967, reports foraminifera of Zemorrian age in Blakeley Formation and faunas of Refugian, Zemorrian and Nazarian age in the Twin River Formation.
Fifes Peak Andesite is older than Yakima basalt (see WAMv) (Warren, 1941).  Fifes Peak Formation yielded radiometric ages of 16.9-24.2 Ma (Dragovich and others, 2002).
K-Ar dating of hornblende from andesite yielded age of 50.3 Ma (Waggoner, 1990a).  Plant fossils in tuffaceous sandstones probably of Oligocene age (Becraft and Weis, 1963).

Early Permian to Devonian range based on fusulinids in the limestone (Brandon and others, 1988).  Outcrops in Stevens County contain Late Mississippian (Meramecian to Chesterian) conodonts and Famennian (Late Devonian) conodonts and macrofossils (Stoffel and others, 1991).

The age of the Windermere Group is constrained between the Lower Cambrian and Upper Paleozoic Addy and Gypsy Quartzites (see WACq) and the inception of rifting around 750 Ma; the Belt Supergroup underlies the Windermere Group and overlies basement rock which yielded isotopic ages of 1,700 Ma; the Deer Trail Group and Priest River Group are correlated to subunits of the Belt Supergroup (Stoffel and others, 1991).  The Maitlen Phyllite is considered Early Cambrian based on paleosponges (Waggoner, 1990b).

The maximum age of the Windermere Group is approximately 750 Ma, based on the inception of rifting; the most reliable age of the metavolcanics of the Huckleberry Formation (though not included in this unit, presumed to have been deposited at or shortly after the extrusion of these rocks) is 762 Ma (Stoffel and others, 1991).
Entire Deer Trail Group has been correlated with the Belt Supergroup, of maximum age 1,700 Ma and minimum age 762 Ma (Stoffel and others, 1991).

This unit intrudes into the Proterozoic Prichard Formation (Belt Supergroup--see WAPC); may also be correlative with rocks from Bonners Ferry, Idaho, which yielded a U-Pb zircon age of 1,433 Ma (Stoffel and others, 1991).

Monk Formation tentatively placed at base of Cambrian (Park and Cannon, 1943) because of stratigraphic position below Gypsy Quartzite (see unit WACq).  Windermere Group is generally considered to be Proterozoic, however, whose mazimum age, based on the beginning of rifting, has been approximated at 750 Ma; the Maitlen Phyllite is interbedded with a metacarbonate unit containing Early Cambrian fauna (Stoffel and others, 1991).

K-Ar ages for Huckleberry Formation:  238-928 Ma and cluster between 613-862 Ma (but may not accurately reflect extrusion); Sm-Nd isochron ages: 674+/-212 Ma, 762+/-44 Ma; 795+/-115 Ma (762 Ma most reliable) (Stoffel eand others, 1991).  Leola volcanics are thought to be correlative with the Huckleberry Formation (Joseph, 1990a).

Foraminifera and gastropods from Blue Mountain unit indicate early to middle Eocene age; no substantiated pre-Tertiary fossils have been found in the Olympic peninsula (Tabor and Cady, 1978).  Radiolarian fauna in Russell Ranch Formation indicate Triassic(?), Jurassic, and Early Cretaceous age (Walsh and others, 1987).

Tabor and others, 1993, include the rocks of King County in the eastern melange belt of early Tertiary (Paleocene) to mid-Cretaceous.   Tabor and others, 1988, include the rocks of Skagit County in the Chilliwack Group of Late Paleozoic age (based on fossils in clastic beds); metamorphism occurred in the Late Cretaceous.

Stoffel and others, 1991, considers the Swakane biotite gneiss to be preCambrian in age; Dragovich and others, 2002, considers the Swakane gneiss to be preTertiary but notes that it includes rounded zircons of more than 1,650 Ma.  The Skagit gneiss consists of 45 Ma granitic plugs and dikes, 60-75 Ma tonalite and tonalitic gneiss, and Triassic-Permian schist, quartzite, amphibolite, and calc-silicate rocks (Stoffel and others, 1991).  The Eldorado Orthogneiss yielded zircon U-Pb ages of 88 to 92 Ma; Gabriel Peak orthogneiss yielded an isotopic decay age of 68 Ma (Dragovich and others, 2002).  The Excelsior Mountain orthogneiss of the Tonga Formation yielded a zircon U-Pb age of 90 Ma  (Duggan and Brown, 1994).

K-Ar and Rb-Sr dating indicates that the blueschist facies of the Easton Metamorphic Suite is mostly Early Cretaceous (Duggan and Brown, 1994).  The Shuksan Greenschist has yielded K-Arand Sr-Rb ages indicating metamorphism at 110 to 130 Ma, with a protolith of Middle to Late Jurassic age (Dragovich and others, 2002).

Duggan and Brown, 1994, report a zircon U-Pb age of 163 ma for the Darrington Phyllite.  Dragovich and others, 2002, report metamorphism at 110-130 Ma, based on K-Ar and Sr-Rb dating, with a protolith of Middle to Late Jurassic age.  The Peshastin Formation is minimally Jurassic in age (Dragovich and others, 2002).

The western melange belt in this unit contains radiolarians in chert and megafossils in argillite of Late Jurassic to Early Cretaceous age; the eastern melange belt in this unit contains radiolarians in chert of Late Triassic to Jurassic age; in general, both are considered to be mid-Cretaceous to Paleocene in age (Tabor and others, 1988).

The metamorphic rocks in Okanogan County, including the Leecher Metamorphics and the Salmon Creek schist and gneisses, yielded K-Ar ages of 100 Ma, and are intruded by Cretaceous plutons, possibly upper Triassic in the case of the Salmon Creek schist (Stoffel and others, 1991). The Tonga Formation may be correlative with the Lookout Mountain Formation which is pre-Late Jurassic; the Chiwaukum schist is early Jurassic to latest Triassic based on Rb-Sr data; the Cascade River Schist yielded U-Pb ages from metatuff of 220 Ma (Dragovich and others, 2002).

Must be older than Mt. Stuart batholith (pre-Cretaceous) (Tabor and others, 1982).  Gabbro in the Ingalls Tectonic Complex yielded a zircon U-Pb age of 155 Ma; while this lithology is not included in this particular portion of the the Complex, it can be assumed that the Hawkins and Peshatin Formations are of similar age (Dragovich and others, 2002).

Turtleback Complex has yielded hornblende (from meta-gabbro) K-Ar age of 554 Ma and zircon U-Pb age of 507 Ma; Yellow Aster Complex yielded U-Th-Pb ages of 370 to 400 Ma and zircon U-Pb ages of 330-390 Ma; concordont zircon U-Pb ages for Marblemount indicated 220 Ma age of crystallization and K-Ar age of about 94 Ma for metamorphism (Dragovich and others, 2002).

Amphibolite at Vedder Mtn (B.C. just north of Washington State) dated at 250 Ma (Misch, 1977).  Gneiss of Yellow Aster Complex yielded U-Pb zircon age of 1,452 to 2,000 Ma, the former considered the minimum protolith age; metamorphic sphene yielded U-Pb age of 415 Ma, considered the metamorphic age; other U-Pb ages reported for parts of the Yellow Aster Complex which is mapped in other units (see WApPMg) range from 370 to 406 Ma (Dragovich and others, 2002).  Amphibolite at Vedder Mtn (B.C. just north of Washington State) dated at 250 Ma (Misch, 1977).  Outcrops in Kittitas County tentatively correlated to the Lookout Mountain Formation which is pre-157 Ma, based on age of quartz diorite intrusion (Walsh and others, 1987).

Contains Pliocene and Miocene foraminiferal and macrofossil faunas (Dragovich and others, 2002).  Rau, 1970, reports that the Quinault Formation represents an upper part of the upper Tertiary-lower Quaternary sequence in which the stratigraphic distribution of foraminifera is in the Repettian to lower Hallian stages (mostly Pliocene).

Walsh and others, 1987, considers this Quaternary to Pliocene; Phillips, 1987, considers the Troutdale Formation to be Pleistocene-Miocene; Tolan and Beeson, 1984, consider the Troutdale Formation to be Pliocene-Miocene.
Basalt of Bear Prairie along Columbia River (Boring lava) yielded K-Ar age of 1.53+/-0.2 Ma; basalt of Battle Ground (Boring lava) yielded carbon-14 age of 20,000+/-400 yr. (Phillips, 1987).

The ribbon chert of the Constitution Formation yielded Late Jurassic or Early Cretaceous radiolaria (Brandon and others, 1988).  Scattered quartz diorite bodies in greenstone of Haystack Terrane yielded U-Pb ages of 160-170 Ma (Whetten and others, 1988).   The Chuckanut Formation is considered to be Eocene in age (see WAEPKc) and the Darrington Phyllite is considered to be Jurassic in age (see WApJph).

The serpentinite of this unit is likely to be of the same age as the adjacent gabbro of WAbi; U-Pb dating of the gabbro indicted Late Jurassic in age (Southwick, 1974).  This age cannot be assumed for the entire complex, though the unit was implaced prior to the intrusion of the Mt. Stuart batholith and must be entirely pre-Cretaceous (Tabor and others, 1982).  Dragovich and others, 2002, suggests that these rocks are similar in age to dated portions of the ophiolite complexes: U-Pb zircon ages of 160-170 Ma for the Fidalgo Complex and U-Pb zircon age of 155 Ma for the Ingalls Tectonic Complex.  The Chopaka Intrusive Complex in Okanogan County is Permian to Triassic in age (see also WApTbi); these rocks make up a very small part of this unit, however.

Age range questionable: based on compositional similarity of Asnola Gabbro to pre-Jurassic rocks and on spatial relationship and compositional similarily of Palmer Mountain greenstone to Triassic-Permian rocks (Stoffel and others, 1991, Rinehart and Fox, 1972). The Chopaka intrusive complex yielded a K-Ar age of 190 Ma, this being interpreted as the age of metamorphism (Early Jurassic) (Stoffel and others, 1991).
U-Pb zircon ages of 160-170 Ma for the Fidalgo Complex (Dragovich and others, 2002).

Phyllite from Anarchist Group on Buckhorn Mtn contains Permian (?) corals (Stoffel and others, 1991).  Limestone in Spectacle Formation (Okanogan County) contains (Late?) Permian brachiopods (Rinehart and Fox, 1972).

Gabbro in the Ingalls Tectonic Complex yields a U-Pb zircon age of 155 Ma.  Metasedimentary rocks contain Late Triassic and Jurassic radiolarians and yield a K-Ar hornblende age of 121 Ma (Dragovich and others, 2002).
Amphibolite in the Tenas Mary Creek complex yielded K-Ar ages of 67.2 and 50.4 Ma--these are probably not magmatic ages; orthogneiss yielded Late Mesozoic Rb-Sr and U-Pb zircon ages (Stoffel, 1990).

Ordovician graptolites found in northern Stevens County (Yates, 1964).  The Covada Group sedimentary rocks have yielded detrital zircon U-Pb early Proterozoic ages; greenstones and limestones contain Ordovician trilobites and conodonts, respectively (Joseph, 1990b).
Map legend says Recent.

Mostly early and middle Pleistocene.Suggested boundaries: 616+/-60 ka (based on K-Ar age of overlying lava flow) and 730 ka (based on magnetism) (Easterbrook, 1986).  Jones, 1999, places Logan Hill Formation at older than 100 ka.
Probably early Pleistocene.
Mostly early and middle Pleistocene.
Map legend says Recent.

Jones, 1999, places the Salmon Springs glaciation between 60 and 80 ka; the Hayden Creek Drift was deposited at the end of the Stade and the Wingate Hill Drift was deposited at the beginning.   The Vashon Stade occurred between 12 and 20 ka; the Sumas Stade is just older than 10 ka.

Date obtained from peat in Vashon Stade on Marrowstone Island: 18,000+/-400 years. Other radiocarbon dates for advance of Vashon Drift at 18,700, 18,000 and 17,800; retreat of Vashon Drift dated at 13,000 to 14,000 years ago. Possession Drift dated at 80 ka (Easterbrook, 1986).  Jones, 1999, places the Possession Drift between 60 and 80 ka and the Whidbey Formation between 80 and 100 ka.Should be mostly Wisconsin in age (70 ka to present) in order to distinguish from Qg2.

Date obtained from peat in Vashon Stade deposits on Marrowstone Island: 18,000+/-400 years (Easterbrook, 1976a).  Jones, 1999, places the Vashon Stade at 12 to 20 ka.Probably mostly Wisconsin in age with possible exception of scabland deposits which may be more recent.
Date obtained from peat in Vashon Stade deposits on Marrowstone Island: 18,000+/-400 years (Easterbrook, 1976a).  Jones, 1999, places the Vashon Stade at 12 to 20 ka.Principally Wisconsin in age.

Mostly pre-Wisconsin in age.  Orting Drift may be about 2 million years old.  Double Bluff Drift between 150-250 ka based on amino acid age estimates. (Easterbrook, 1986). Jones, 1999, places the Possession Drift between 60 and 80 ka and the Whidbey Formation between 80 and 100 ka.  Jones, 1999, also places the Double Bluff Drift, the Stuck Drift, the Alderton Formation, and the Orting Drift, from youngest to oldest respectively (although the Double Bluff Drift and the the Stuck Drift may actually be the same age) at greater than 100 ka.
The Osceola mudflow is younger than 10 ka (Jones, 1999).
Majority of deposits 19,000 to 70,000 years old (Tabor and Cady, 1978).

Luedke and others, 1983, dates this unit as 0-5 Ma with less than 10% of Holocene age.  Mt. Rainier andesite yielded K-Ar ages of 300,000 and 660,000 yr; Mt. St. Helens ranges in age from 250 to 40,000 yr. (Walsh and others, 1987).

Corals and conodonts of limestone indicate Frasnian age and early Givetian, Lochkovian, Emsian, Eifelian, and Ludlow ages; monograptids from slate indicated late Silurian; monograptids from argillite and siltstone indicate Silurian to Early Devonian (Joseph, 1990a).
K-Ar date (biotite) in shonkinite of 49.7+/-1.5 Ma (Eocene) (Yates and Engels 1968).  Cretaceous or Jurassic age suggested of syenite near Shasket Creek, northern Ferry County (Stoffel, 1990).

Outcrop in Okanogan County probably lower (?) Eocene (Rinehart and Fox, 1972).   Single pollen analysis from Huntingdon Formation in Whatcom County is upper Eocene to lower Oligocene; either concordant or overlying Chuckanut formation of middle to late Eocene age (Dragovich and others, 2002).  The Tiger Formation contains middle Eocene palynomorphs and is locally gradational with units of 42 to 49 Ma (based on fission-track zircon dating) (Stoffel and others, 1991).

Dragovich and others, 2002, reports that the Twin Sisters Dunite is 85-100 Ma.  Outcrops in Snohomish County considered a part of the eastern melange belt of mid-Cretaceous to Paleocene age (Tabor and others, 1988).

PROBABLY MOSTLY EOCENE BUT INCLUDES WIDE RANGE:U-Pb (zircon) and K-Ar (biotite) dates for Index batholith both 34 Ma, K-Ar dates for Snoqualmie batholith range from 18 to 25 Ma, and K-Ar dates for Grotto batholith range from 23 to 25 Ma (Tabor and others, 1993).  U-Pb date on sphene of Oval Peak batholith yields 65.3 Ma age (Miller, 1987).  Oval Peak batholith, Fawn Peak Stock, and Pasayten Stock-Dike may actually be Cretaceous in age (Barksdale, 1975), supported in part by K-Ar dating of Pasayten and Rock Creek dikes yielding 86.1 to 87.7 Ma (Tabor and others, 1968).  Castle Peak stock yields K-Ar date of 49.5 Ma; Monument Peak stock of 47.9 Ma; Golden Horn batholith of 46.6 Ma (Tabor and others, 1968).  K-Ar date on biotite of Golden Horn Granodiorite places intrusion at Eocene-Oligocene boundary (c. 36.6 Ma) as well (Barksdale, 1975).  Granodiorite of Silver Star Pluton yielded K-Ar age of 19.6 Ma (Phillips, 1987, Walsh and others, 1987).

Rhyodacite body in Stevens County yielded K-Ar date of 49.8+/-1.5 Ma (Yates and Engels, 1968).  Basalt sills in the southwestern corner of the state yielded K-Ar ages of 9 to 16 Ma (Snavely and others, 1973).  Wild Mountain quartz diorite yielded K-Ar age of 4.9 Ma (Walsh and others, 1987).

Metagabbro and metatonalite units of Tabor and others, 1993, yield U-Th-Pb zircon ages of 170 to 150 Ma.  Most Western melange belt componants contain Late Jurassic to Early Cretaceous radiolarian chert or mega-fossil bearing argillite (Dragovich and others, 2002).

Dragovich and others, 2002 maps most of this unit as Eocene in age: the Chuckanut Formation yielded a zircon fission-track age of 49.9 Ma as well as palynomorphs believed to be middle to late Eocene in age; the Chumstick Formation yielded fission track ages ranging from 42 to 49 Ma; the Swauk Formation yielded zircon fission-track ages of 50 to 52 Ma and is overlain by the Teenaway Formation of 47 Ma.

K-Ar hornblende age of 90 Ma and zircon age of 90 Ma in Black Peak Batholith of Okanogan County (Miller, 1987).  The Jordan Lakes pluton yielded U-Pb ages ranging from 58 to 90 Ma; the Cyclone Lake pluton yielded K-Ar ages of 28 and 57 Ma (Dragovich and others, 2002). Stoffel, 1990, reports K-Ar ages of 51.1 Ma and 53.7 Ma for plutons in Ferry County.
Age applies to entire Midnight Peak Formation (see WAKc).

In Ferry County, Permian age rocks consist of greenstone and lenticular limestone, Triassic age rocks consist of well-bedded limestone, shlae, lesser amounts of greenstone (Parker and Calkins, 1964).  Martin Bridge Formation contains Norian (Late Triassic) age ammonites (Schuster and others, 1997).
Chert clasts in conglomerate yield Triassic radiolarians; pollen in conglomerate of Bald Mountain suggests Late Cretaceous to early Tertiary age (Dragovich and others, 2002).
Foraminferal faunas indicate Nazarian to Zemorrian Stages (Eocene); megafossils indicate Paleocene to late Eocene; fission-track ages ranging from 25.6 to 44.6 Ma (Dragovich and others, 2002).

Carter Mountain Dacite of Eocene age; Twin Peaks Andesite probably equivalent in age (Rinehart and Fox, 1976).  Zircon fission-track ages of 22-24 Ma in Eagle Tuff of King County (Tabor and others, 1993).  K-Ar hornblende and biotite ages range from 43 to 52 Ma
Range based on Smith, 1993, and Dragovich and others, 2002.
